WEBVTT

00:01.986 --> 00:03.768
- Chapter five--
like all families,

00:03.868 --> 00:05.969
the Hayworths shared
their trials and tribulations.

00:06.069 --> 00:09.331
Sarah was still looking
for a full-time job,

00:09.431 --> 00:11.332
but she'd recently
gotten some freelance work.

00:11.432 --> 00:12.853
Of course,
her brothers were nothing

00:12.953 --> 00:14.174
but thrilled and supportive.

00:14.274 --> 00:15.455
- Please stop laughing.

00:15.555 --> 00:18.297
- I'm sorry.
It's--it's kind of funny.

00:18.397 --> 00:19.817
- That's, like, 100%
a real job?

00:19.917 --> 00:21.098
- Yes!
Okay?

00:21.198 --> 00:22.619
I am helping people
get their pets certified

00:22.719 --> 00:24.260
as emotional
support animals.

00:24.360 --> 00:27.382
- So let's just say, I want to
bring a racoon to Six Flags.

00:27.482 --> 00:28.743
You have the power
to make that happen?

00:28.843 --> 00:30.464
- [laughs]

00:30.564 --> 00:32.425
- Okay, it's not what I want
to do for the rest of my life,

00:32.525 --> 00:34.026
but it's a paycheck,

00:34.126 --> 00:35.507
and Denise has been paying
for everything

00:35.607 --> 00:36.708
the past couple months, so...

00:36.808 --> 00:38.189
- Last time
I flew commercial,

00:38.289 --> 00:39.750
I sat right next
to a giant tortoise.

00:39.850 --> 00:42.191
- Okay, what did I miss?

00:42.291 --> 00:43.712
Actually, I don't care.
Thanks.

00:43.812 --> 00:46.394
- Guys, Kelvin
would like the floor.

00:46.494 --> 00:48.795
For school, he has to do
a report on a family member

00:48.895 --> 00:50.076
whose job he admires,

00:50.176 --> 00:51.437
and he's figuring out
who to pick.

00:51.537 --> 00:52.878
- Oh.

00:52.978 --> 00:54.959
- Oh, well.
That can be a tough decision,

00:55.059 --> 00:56.640
but I guess
if you want to learn

00:56.740 --> 00:58.521
from a "New York Times"
best-selling author--

00:58.621 --> 00:59.802
- I choose Uncle Connor.
- What now?

00:59.902 --> 01:01.723
- My guy.
[grunts]

01:01.823 --> 01:03.685
Uncle Connor for the win.

01:03.785 --> 01:05.406
I will not let you down!

01:05.506 --> 01:07.047
- Okay, sweetie.

01:07.147 --> 01:09.648
Um, did you consider
anybody else?

01:09.748 --> 01:11.249
- Nope.

01:11.349 --> 01:12.770
I may not know what
Uncle Connor actually does...

01:12.870 --> 01:15.292
- That's fine.
It's not clear.

01:15.392 --> 01:17.533
- But he definitely
has the coolest job.

01:17.633 --> 01:18.534
- Mm-hmm.
- Look at this place!

01:18.634 --> 01:20.055
- Look at the place.

01:20.155 --> 01:22.016
- Well, you know, Kelvin,
in ancient times,

01:22.116 --> 01:25.498
they used to consider a writer
kind of the first cool job.

01:25.598 --> 01:28.060
- Please stop before you use
the word "scribe."

01:28.160 --> 01:31.382
- Kel, you know you can come
to work with me or Lupe

01:31.482 --> 01:33.343
or even Uncle Tommy.

01:33.443 --> 01:35.665
- I was the last option?
- Ah, hi.

01:35.765 --> 01:37.826
Sarah and I didn't even
make the list.

01:37.926 --> 01:39.587
You know, what I do at home
is actually harder

01:39.687 --> 01:41.108
than what I did
at the law firm,

01:41.208 --> 01:42.829
but because I don't make
any dinero,

01:42.929 --> 01:44.030
it's not considered a job.

01:44.130 --> 01:46.831
- Actually,
I did just get a job.

01:46.931 --> 01:48.673
Yeah, it's a mildly
unethical one, but still...

01:48.773 --> 01:50.394
- Oh, is unethical, like,

01:50.494 --> 01:53.916
a disqualifier
for this school-project thing?

01:54.016 --> 01:56.377
- ♪ Hey, hey, hey, hey ♪

02:00.260 --> 02:02.041
- Twins finally go to sleep?
- Yeah.

02:02.141 --> 02:03.342
I just started telling them
about what I did for a living.

02:03.422 --> 02:04.442
Put them right out.

02:04.542 --> 02:05.723
- Still mad Kelvin
didn't pick you?

02:05.823 --> 02:07.044
- Nah, no, look.

02:07.144 --> 02:09.445
Sweetie, you see,
being a novelist

02:09.545 --> 02:10.806
isn't just cool.

02:10.906 --> 02:13.688
It's lit...erature.

02:13.788 --> 02:15.889
Literature.
We'll workshop that.

02:15.989 --> 02:18.011
And, yeah, I guess I'm a little
over-sensitive about work.

02:18.111 --> 02:20.452
I've been stuck on the same
stupid chapter for weeks.

02:20.552 --> 02:22.373
- Honey, you've had
writer's block before.

02:22.473 --> 02:23.734
You always get through it,

02:23.834 --> 02:27.056
but if you aren't
working anyway,

02:27.156 --> 02:28.537
could you watch
the twins tomorrow

02:28.637 --> 02:30.018
so I can run some errands?

02:30.118 --> 02:31.819
- Actually, they say
with writer's block,

02:31.919 --> 02:33.701
the best thing to do
is to kind of stay on task.

02:33.801 --> 02:35.502
- Honey, I don't need to know
your whole process.

02:35.602 --> 02:36.943
Can you help out or not?

02:37.043 --> 02:38.183
- Yeah, yeah.
No, yeah.

02:38.283 --> 02:39.904
[children screaming and crying]

02:40.004 --> 02:42.006
- Great, thank you.
- I can--yeah.

02:46.729 --> 02:48.750
Your mom seemed
a little annoyed, huh?

02:48.850 --> 02:51.031
- She was just cooking dinner
while folding laundry,

02:51.131 --> 02:52.952
and then she had
to ask you for help.

02:53.052 --> 02:54.433
- Oh.

02:54.533 --> 02:57.195
- And now she's changing
two diapers.

02:57.295 --> 02:58.876
- You know what?
You're right, you're right.

02:58.976 --> 03:00.557
Mom does so much
around here.

03:00.657 --> 03:04.239
I got to start
helping out more.

03:04.339 --> 03:05.520
Honey, with puzzles,

03:05.620 --> 03:06.841
if you start
with the corner pieces,

03:06.941 --> 03:08.362
it makes it a lot easier--
- Dad!

03:08.462 --> 03:10.043
- Okay, I'm helping.
I'm helping, okay.

03:10.143 --> 03:13.005
[quirky music]

03:13.105 --> 03:14.486
♪ ♪

03:14.586 --> 03:16.487
- Hey.

03:16.587 --> 03:17.608
- Hey!

03:17.708 --> 03:19.709
One sec.

03:20.549 --> 03:22.611
- Okay, okay, just come here,
just real quick.

03:22.711 --> 03:24.172
Mmm.

03:24.272 --> 03:25.533
- Yep.
Okay.

03:25.633 --> 03:26.853
- Time to let go, Sarah.

03:26.953 --> 03:28.334
- Just one more minute.
I'm not ready.

03:28.434 --> 03:29.655
- Sarah.

03:29.755 --> 03:31.216
- Okay, fine,
fine, fine, fine, fine.

03:31.316 --> 03:32.657
- I know Connor may not be
the best mentor for Kelvin,

03:32.757 --> 03:34.098
but I'm picking him up at 4:30.

03:34.198 --> 03:36.019
How much damage can he do?

03:36.119 --> 03:37.900
Okay, 4:15.

03:38.000 --> 03:39.581
- Okay, hey, buddy,

03:39.681 --> 03:42.863
no matter what your uncle says,
money is not the solution.

03:42.963 --> 03:44.945
It's the problem.

03:45.045 --> 03:47.826
Remember who you are.

03:47.926 --> 03:49.928
- Okay.

03:51.609 --> 03:53.110
- All right!

03:53.210 --> 03:55.751
Get to hang out at my home
office on a school day?

03:55.851 --> 03:58.033
This is gonna rule ass.

03:58.133 --> 03:59.794
Sorry. Rule butt.

03:59.894 --> 04:01.315
Hey, Kel, there's some
green juice in the kitchen.

04:01.415 --> 04:03.396
You want to go knock back
some anti-oxies?

04:03.496 --> 04:05.477
- Yeah, I do.
- Go knock them back, bud.

04:05.577 --> 04:07.519
[chuckles]

04:07.619 --> 04:09.760
- [sighs]
- What?

04:09.860 --> 04:11.921
- Just please don't send
my son home saying,

04:12.021 --> 04:13.803
"Crushed it, bro."

04:13.903 --> 04:15.804
- Okay, first off,

04:15.904 --> 04:18.125
they're saying "bruh" now.

04:18.225 --> 04:19.526
Second, what the hell, bruh?

04:19.626 --> 04:21.127
Been super rude
ever since Kelvin decided

04:21.227 --> 04:22.408
he wanted to be just like me.

04:22.508 --> 04:24.049
- Okay, I don't know
where you got that.

04:24.149 --> 04:25.570
That's not
at all what he said, so...

04:25.670 --> 04:27.651
- Sarah, Connor's generously
sharing his time today.

04:27.751 --> 04:29.893
- And my disciplined approach
to market risk informed

04:29.993 --> 04:31.894
by levelheaded
financial analysis.

04:31.994 --> 04:33.175
I'm not gonna corrupt your son.

04:33.275 --> 04:35.496
- So you just got
a giant see-through house

04:35.596 --> 04:37.617
with ocean views
by never doing anything shady?

04:37.717 --> 04:39.979
- [laughs]
That's a bay, genius!

04:40.079 --> 04:41.420
We don't live in
"the Ocean Area"!

04:41.520 --> 04:43.461
- Now we're yelling.
- And you want to talk shady?

04:43.561 --> 04:45.582
You're the one helping
cat ladies cheat the system!

04:45.682 --> 04:48.344
- Some of them are legitimately
scared to dine alone.

04:48.444 --> 04:50.065
- Are they?
- Some of them are!

04:50.165 --> 04:52.306
- Okay,
and now we're calming down.

04:52.406 --> 04:54.868
Smell the flowers.
Cool the soup.

04:54.968 --> 04:56.869
- What are you doing?
- This is a breathing technique

04:56.969 --> 04:58.590
I use on my second-graders
when they tantrum.

04:58.690 --> 05:00.992
[both breathing deeply]
- Okay, there it is.

05:01.092 --> 05:03.033
All right,
it's time to go, Lulu.

05:03.133 --> 05:05.955
- Okay, have fun exploiting the
masses and raping the planet.

05:06.055 --> 05:08.276
- Have a great day illegally
prescribing Shar Peis!

05:08.376 --> 05:10.378
- I'll pick him up by myself.

05:11.618 --> 05:14.160
- Okay, mi'jita.
Let's go, school!

05:14.260 --> 05:15.601
Hey, thanks
for taking the boys.

05:15.701 --> 05:17.642
- Ah, no problem.
Hey, you look good today.

05:17.742 --> 05:20.524
- How do I usually look?
- Uh, no, no.

05:20.624 --> 05:22.445
I'm just saying it's been
a long time since I've seen you

05:22.545 --> 05:25.087
with jewelry that you
didn't find in a Happy Meal.

05:25.187 --> 05:27.408
Hey, I did the laundry,
even though you didn't ask me.

05:27.508 --> 05:28.689
- Camila, honey?

05:28.789 --> 05:30.810
Could you draw your daddy
a gold medal?

05:30.910 --> 05:33.052
- [laughs]
Ha, ha, I deserve that.

05:33.152 --> 05:34.413
But I just want you to know,

05:34.513 --> 05:35.974
I'm gonna start
stepping it up around here.

05:36.074 --> 05:38.095
In fact, this is a list
of everything

05:38.195 --> 05:40.456
that I am gonna take off
your plate today.

05:40.556 --> 05:42.738
I guess I could start
by crossing off "do laundry."

05:42.838 --> 05:44.419
- Impressive!

05:44.519 --> 05:47.140
So you also did the four loads
in the babies' hamper?

05:47.240 --> 05:49.262
- I wanted to save that
for later.

05:49.362 --> 05:51.183
You know, give myself
a little treat?

05:51.283 --> 05:53.705
- Okay, have a good day.
Te quiero. Camila, vámonos!

05:53.805 --> 05:55.546
- Love you!
- Love you.

05:55.646 --> 05:57.647
- Oh.

05:59.248 --> 06:01.309
You know, the period after Dad
kind of seems like a choice.

06:01.409 --> 06:04.151
- Andele, get in the car.
I'll see you in there.

06:04.251 --> 06:06.633
[sneaky music]

06:06.733 --> 06:09.714
[line trilling]

06:09.814 --> 06:12.596
Hi. I'm running
a few minutes late.

06:12.696 --> 06:14.237
Okay.
Thank you so much.

06:14.337 --> 06:15.758
- Hey!

06:15.858 --> 06:17.960
Do I use "permanent press"
on the twins' laundry?

06:18.060 --> 06:21.041
Also, what is
"permanent press"?

06:21.141 --> 06:22.602
You know what?
I'm gonna figure it out myself.

06:22.702 --> 06:24.444
So no problem.

06:24.544 --> 06:26.005
♪ ♪

06:26.105 --> 06:28.286
- So what I do, Kelvin,

06:28.386 --> 06:32.849
is a little thing I like
to call private equity.

06:32.949 --> 06:34.930
Basically,
I take money from my company,

06:35.030 --> 06:39.453
put it into other companies
to eventually make more money.

06:39.553 --> 06:41.774
I also do a bit of,
uh, venture cap,

06:41.874 --> 06:43.736
bit of day trading--
got it?

06:43.836 --> 06:46.497
- I definitely got the part
about more money.

06:46.597 --> 06:47.978
- That's all you need to know.

06:48.078 --> 06:50.140
- Then why's the diagram
so complicated?

06:50.240 --> 06:53.101
- Because, Kelvin...
scented markers.

06:53.201 --> 06:55.863
Yeah.
The brown one's root beer.

06:55.963 --> 06:57.624
- ♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah,
I'm a boss now ♪

06:57.724 --> 06:58.905
♪ It's in the way I walk ♪
- ♪ The way I walk ♪

06:59.005 --> 07:00.706
- ♪ I'm a boss now ♪

07:00.806 --> 07:02.387
♪ It's in the way I talk ♪
- ♪ The way I talk ♪

07:02.487 --> 07:05.029
♪ I'm a boss now,
dropping 50 grand, hey ♪

07:05.129 --> 07:06.990
♪ I'm a boss now,
bottles in my hand ♪

07:07.090 --> 07:08.751
♪ Put another dub
up in the record book ♪

07:08.851 --> 07:10.512
♪ Bottom shook ♪

07:10.612 --> 07:12.153
♪ Freshest in the business,
ooh, they got to look ♪

07:12.253 --> 07:14.995
♪ Celebrating every day
just because we getting paid ♪

07:15.095 --> 07:17.076
♪ Turning up and misbehave, go
and get it, don't hesitate ♪

07:17.176 --> 07:20.438
- Come on, you got to work
with me here a little bit, man.

07:20.538 --> 07:22.480
Yeah, we can live with that.

07:22.580 --> 07:24.161
[cell phone beeps]

07:24.261 --> 07:26.002
Pizza's gonna be here
in 20 minutes.

07:26.102 --> 07:27.523
- ♪ Told them all
about the new name ♪

07:27.623 --> 07:29.724
- Whoo!

07:29.824 --> 07:32.626
Ooh, ooh, ooh, ooh.

07:35.628 --> 07:37.569
- These people need help,
you're gonna help them.

07:37.669 --> 07:39.330
Hello, I'm Sarah.

07:39.430 --> 07:41.471
Hello, I'm Sarah.

07:43.072 --> 07:45.494
Hi, I'm Sarah.
How are you today?

07:45.594 --> 07:47.535
- I guess I'm not too great.

07:47.635 --> 07:49.416
I have terrible anxiety.

07:49.516 --> 07:51.017
So how often would you say

07:51.117 --> 07:53.059
that you suffer
from your anxiety?

07:53.159 --> 07:55.100
- I guess whenever I don't
have DeeDee by my side.

07:55.200 --> 07:56.341
- [chirps]

07:56.441 --> 07:59.543
- Oh.
Oh, DeeDee is a parrot.

07:59.643 --> 08:01.704
- DeeDee is a cockatiel.
[bird screeches]

08:01.804 --> 08:03.825
Are you even a therapist?

08:03.925 --> 08:05.586
- [whispering] It doesn't
always feel like it.

08:05.686 --> 08:07.988
[smooth music]

08:08.088 --> 08:10.629
- Marina, you made it!

08:10.729 --> 08:13.351
- Hi.
I'm so sorry I'm late.

08:13.451 --> 08:15.432
[cell phone chimes]
Oh.

08:15.532 --> 08:18.594
[chuckles]

08:18.694 --> 08:20.636
This will just be one moment.

08:20.736 --> 08:22.677
Husband problems,
you know what I mean?

08:22.777 --> 08:24.838
- My husband died
two years ago.

08:24.938 --> 08:27.040
- I remembered that
just as I said it.

08:27.140 --> 08:30.602
♪ ♪

08:30.702 --> 08:33.324
- Perfect.

08:33.424 --> 08:35.605
Boys, we got work to do.
Hands in the middle.

08:35.705 --> 08:38.126
[baby cooing]

08:38.226 --> 08:41.168
Come on, be a team player.

08:41.268 --> 08:44.250
Okay, one's good enough for me.
And go!

08:44.350 --> 08:46.732
[Salt-N-Pepa's "Whatta Man"]

08:46.832 --> 08:48.333
[grunts]

08:48.433 --> 08:49.614
One, two.

08:49.714 --> 08:52.335
Yeah.
[laughs]

08:52.435 --> 08:55.257
♪ What a mighty good man,
gotta say it again now ♪

08:55.357 --> 08:57.499
♪ What a man, what a man,
what a man ♪

08:57.599 --> 08:59.099
♪ What a mighty good man ♪

08:59.199 --> 09:01.381
♪ He's a mighty,
mighty good man ♪

09:01.481 --> 09:02.662
♪ So here's to the future ♪

09:02.762 --> 09:04.343
♪ 'Cause we got through
the past ♪

09:04.443 --> 09:05.443
♪ I finally found somebody
that can make me laugh ♪

09:05.523 --> 09:07.505
- Yeah.

09:07.605 --> 09:09.866
- [laughs]
♪ You so crazy ♪

09:09.966 --> 09:11.947
♪ I think I wanna have
your baby ♪

09:12.047 --> 09:14.349
♪ What a man, what a man,
what a man ♪

09:14.449 --> 09:16.110
♪ What a mighty good man ♪

09:16.210 --> 09:18.391
- Move Connor's divorce
back a chapter.

09:18.491 --> 09:21.433
End that section
with Tom asking for the loan.

09:21.533 --> 09:22.754
I know.

09:22.854 --> 09:24.595
Why didn't
I think about that sooner?

09:24.695 --> 09:26.156
[both gurgling]

09:26.256 --> 09:27.957
Bon appétit!

09:28.057 --> 09:30.999
- ♪ What a man,
what a man, what a man ♪

09:31.099 --> 09:33.001
♪ What a mighty good man ♪

09:33.101 --> 09:35.322
♪ What a man,
what a man, what a man ♪

09:35.422 --> 09:36.763
♪ What a mighty good man ♪

09:36.863 --> 09:38.404
- So will
one of these certificates

09:38.504 --> 09:40.325
cover multiple cats?
- Uh, no.

09:40.425 --> 09:42.566
You need one certificate
for each animal.

09:42.666 --> 09:45.768
How--how many certificates
do you need?

09:45.868 --> 09:47.570
- I would--

09:47.670 --> 09:49.451
I would have to count them.

09:49.551 --> 09:51.692
I'll call you back.
It's gonna be a while.

09:51.792 --> 09:53.013
- Okay.

09:53.113 --> 09:54.854
[sighing]
Oh, my God.

09:54.954 --> 09:57.736
[cell phone ringing]

09:57.836 --> 09:59.177
Hi, Lulu.

09:59.277 --> 10:01.098
- Hey, Lulu.
How's work?

10:01.198 --> 10:03.419
- Well, I learned
a lot about iguanas.

10:03.519 --> 10:06.421
And I made $62

10:06.521 --> 10:07.622
after taxes.
[door closes]

10:07.722 --> 10:09.263
- Ooh, yes!
Bring home the bacon.

10:09.363 --> 10:11.785
- Yeah.
- Well, soy bacon for us.

10:11.885 --> 10:14.346
I picked up Shamiah, and now
we are at Connor's house.

10:14.446 --> 10:15.907
- Ah, great.
Bring Kelvin home

10:16.007 --> 10:17.548
before he ends up
in a white-collar prison.

10:17.648 --> 10:19.109
- Well, at least
he'll have his own room there.

10:19.209 --> 10:21.210
- [chuckles] Okay, bye.
- Okay, bye.

10:22.411 --> 10:25.193
Kel?
Kel!

10:25.293 --> 10:26.674
- Shh, Mom!

10:26.774 --> 10:30.716
- No, Jerry, we had
a verbal contract in place,

10:30.816 --> 10:32.798
and now you're getting
scared on me.

10:32.898 --> 10:35.039
- We're trying to buy
40% of a tree care company,

10:35.139 --> 10:36.720
but the owner
wants to weasel out.

10:36.820 --> 10:38.521
- Do not make me the bad guy.

10:38.621 --> 10:40.723
I swear to God, Jerry.

10:40.823 --> 10:42.324
That's funny, Jerry!

10:42.424 --> 10:44.005
- I don't know
what you learned here today,

10:44.105 --> 10:45.566
but that is not how
we talk to people.

10:45.666 --> 10:48.567
- What are you talking about?
He's got Jerry by the plugs!

10:48.667 --> 10:49.848
- No.
- What?

10:49.948 --> 10:52.130
- Oh.
God!

10:52.230 --> 10:53.691
He went down to 20.

10:53.791 --> 10:56.372
Slippery bastard!
Hey, Denise.

10:56.472 --> 10:59.254
- Hey, everything okay?
- No.

10:59.354 --> 11:02.296
I've tried everything
with this guy--screaming,

11:02.396 --> 11:04.297
yelling, shouting,
I even raised my voice.

11:04.397 --> 11:05.458
- Ooh, yeah, I get it.

11:05.558 --> 11:07.739
I work with seven-year-olds
all day.

11:07.839 --> 11:10.381
You know what would work
better than getting loud?

11:10.481 --> 11:12.062
- [sighs]
What?

11:12.162 --> 11:15.944
- That is a really nice
shirt on you--very flattering.

11:16.044 --> 11:17.866
- Thanks, I just got it.
- Oh, it looks good, yeah.

11:17.966 --> 11:19.627
Can I borrow
your car next week?

11:19.727 --> 11:21.868
- Of course, yeah.

11:21.968 --> 11:25.110
Oh, being nice, yes!
- Yeah.

11:25.210 --> 11:26.471
- You want me to try that
with Jerry?

11:26.571 --> 11:28.352
- No, I don't.
- Hey, Jer, real quick--

11:28.452 --> 11:30.153
I'm gonna put my operating
partner on the phone, okay?

11:30.253 --> 11:33.155
- I've never really--I don't--
all: Mom, talk to Jerry!

11:33.255 --> 11:34.836
- Hi, Jerry.
This is Denise.

11:34.936 --> 11:36.597
Sorry about my partner.

11:36.697 --> 11:41.400
Uh, he's just so passionate
about tree-care equipment, yes.

11:41.500 --> 11:43.041
And I can tell
you're still upset.

11:43.141 --> 11:44.962
Okay, let's do some breathing,
Jerry, okay?

11:45.062 --> 11:46.323
Smell the bread.
[inhales deeply]

11:46.423 --> 11:47.724
Blow the bubbles.
[exhales deeply]

11:47.824 --> 11:49.365
Good, Jerry.
Good.

11:49.465 --> 11:50.966
You know,
I had an uncle named Jerry.

11:51.066 --> 11:52.327
He was my favorite uncle.

11:52.427 --> 11:54.328
He used to
call me "Niece Denise."

11:54.428 --> 11:56.209
- She doesn't have
an Uncle Jerry.

11:56.309 --> 11:58.251
- You know, Jer-bear,
I am on your side.

11:58.351 --> 12:00.892
Clearly we both love
the environment.

12:00.992 --> 12:04.094
That's why we're
in the tree game, right?

12:04.194 --> 12:07.696
So tell me what I got to do
to get you to sell us 30%?

12:07.796 --> 12:11.339
60%.
Oh, oh.

12:11.439 --> 12:13.780
Oh, you'll go to 35
for Niece Denise?

12:13.880 --> 12:15.902
Okay!
I like hearing that.

12:16.002 --> 12:19.184
And now all we have to do is...

12:19.284 --> 12:20.705
ribbon dance.

12:20.805 --> 12:23.066
Okay, it was good
talking to you. Bye.

12:23.166 --> 12:26.108
- What?
[both laughing]

12:26.208 --> 12:29.470
- Wow!
- Mom, that was amazing!

12:29.570 --> 12:30.951
- You crushed it, bruh!

12:31.051 --> 12:33.633
- Yeah!
I crushed it, bruh!

12:33.733 --> 12:35.153
Ooh, that was exhilarating!

12:35.253 --> 12:36.594
Is that why people
lie all the time?

12:36.694 --> 12:37.835
- It's one
of the reasons, yeah.

12:37.935 --> 12:39.436
How'd you do that?

12:39.536 --> 12:40.957
- Oh, well, you catch
more flies with honey.

12:41.057 --> 12:42.558
- Well, depending on how the
next quarter goes for Jerry,

12:42.658 --> 12:44.119
you might've just made me
a lot of flies.

12:44.219 --> 12:46.160
- Ooh!
[laughs]

12:46.260 --> 12:49.382
- You want to make some more?
- Yeah.

12:52.224 --> 12:53.605
[cell phone buzzes]

12:53.705 --> 12:54.846
- Hey, hon.

12:54.946 --> 12:56.447
- Hey, sweetie.
Errands ran long.

12:56.547 --> 12:58.688
Do you think you could watch
the boys a little longer

12:58.788 --> 13:00.289
and pick Camila up
from after-care?

13:00.389 --> 13:01.770
- Oh, yeah, come on,
that's not gonna be a problem.

13:01.870 --> 13:04.692
- Thank you.
How was your day?

13:04.792 --> 13:06.893
- Yeah, it was
actually incredible.

13:06.993 --> 13:09.335
Turning my brain off
to do housework

13:09.435 --> 13:11.376
and watch the kids actually
got rid of my writer's block.

13:11.476 --> 13:12.657
- Turning your brain off?

13:12.757 --> 13:14.378
So what I do all day
is brainless?

13:14.478 --> 13:15.739
- No!
No, no, no, no.

13:15.839 --> 13:17.540
I'm saying I'm surprised
how much I got done.

13:17.640 --> 13:19.141
The house looks great.
- So I guess

13:19.241 --> 13:21.942
you're more efficient
and a better housekeeper.

13:22.042 --> 13:23.584
- Oh, no, no, no, no.
That's not what I'm saying.

13:23.684 --> 13:26.625
- You know,
all I can do is my best.

13:26.725 --> 13:28.787
- You know, now that
I'm looking around the house,

13:28.887 --> 13:30.588
it's actually still
a kind of a disaster.

13:30.688 --> 13:32.989
I better go.
Okay, bye.

13:33.089 --> 13:34.590
[sighs]
Okay, guys.

13:34.690 --> 13:36.992
Now we got to make
the house less clean.

13:37.092 --> 13:39.353
I know, Daddy sounds crazy.

13:39.453 --> 13:41.114
That's what marriage
is sometimes.

13:41.214 --> 13:43.356
- ♪ Ooh, what a man,
what a man, what a man ♪

13:43.456 --> 13:45.037
♪ What a mighty good man ♪

13:45.137 --> 13:47.518
♪ Yeah, he's a mighty,
mighty good man ♪

13:47.618 --> 13:51.001
- I'll just redistribute
an artful amount of dust.

13:51.101 --> 13:53.402
[grunts]

13:53.502 --> 13:54.963
[babies laughing]

13:55.063 --> 13:57.485
Daddy didn't really think
this one through, did he?

13:57.585 --> 14:00.166
- ♪ What a man,
what a man, what a man ♪

14:00.266 --> 14:01.607
♪ What a mighty good man ♪

14:01.707 --> 14:05.369
♪ I said
what a mighty good man ♪

14:05.469 --> 14:07.211
You know what I'm sayin'?

14:07.311 --> 14:09.772
♪ He's a mighty,
mighty good man ♪

14:09.872 --> 14:11.873
Y'all...

14:12.474 --> 14:13.895
- Okay, you're all set.

14:13.995 --> 14:15.736
- Really?
Oh, you're so nice.

14:15.836 --> 14:18.177
I know a lot of people think
this is all a bunch of hooey,

14:18.277 --> 14:20.059
but if I couldn't take Giblet
on the bus with me,

14:20.159 --> 14:21.619
I don't think
I'd be able to go to work.

14:21.719 --> 14:23.180
- Oh.

14:23.280 --> 14:24.821
- So thank you.

14:24.921 --> 14:27.183
- Oh, you're so welcome.

14:27.283 --> 14:29.865
- Unrelated, you can prescribe
barbiturates, right?

14:29.965 --> 14:31.426
- Nope!
- Uppers, downers?

14:31.526 --> 14:33.527
Betties, Veronicas?
- Uh-uh.

14:34.808 --> 14:36.028
[cell phone rings]
- Hey, Lulu.

14:36.128 --> 14:37.830
- Hey.
Are you guys on your way home?

14:37.930 --> 14:39.070
- Uh, we may go late here.

14:39.170 --> 14:41.552
- We, go--go late?
[chuckles] What?

14:41.652 --> 14:43.953
- Oh, I have another call.
How you doing?

14:44.053 --> 14:45.594
- Hi, Miss Sarah.
- Lupe?

14:45.694 --> 14:46.995
- Connor needed
Denise's help

14:47.095 --> 14:49.277
with a Belgian
crypto situation.

14:49.377 --> 14:52.559
- Okay, wait. I'm sorry.
Denise is helping Connor?

14:52.659 --> 14:54.320
- Yes.
Apparently she's crushing it.

14:54.420 --> 14:55.881
- Lupe, I need more espresso!

14:55.981 --> 14:57.602
Jean-Pierre,
I know you're Belgian,

14:57.702 --> 15:00.764
but you need
to quit waffling on me.

15:00.864 --> 15:04.246
- Okay, the perfect amount
of mess.

15:04.346 --> 15:06.367
Well, maybe one noodle more.

15:06.467 --> 15:08.529
[quirky music]

15:08.629 --> 15:09.889
- What are you doing?
- Oh, boy.

15:09.989 --> 15:11.410
- You're putting pasta
on the wall?

15:11.510 --> 15:14.052
- Uh, huh.

15:14.152 --> 15:15.693
This is gonna sound crazy.

15:15.793 --> 15:17.334
Well, you know what?
Maybe you're gonna love this.

15:17.434 --> 15:19.856
I don't know.
Um, I got the house too clean.

15:19.956 --> 15:23.738
I thought that might annoy you.
Then I made it too dirty again.

15:23.838 --> 15:25.939
I knew that would annoy you.
Then I made it too clean again.

15:26.039 --> 15:27.100
- Where's Camila?

15:27.200 --> 15:28.421
♪ ♪

15:28.521 --> 15:30.262
Did you forget to pick her up?

15:30.362 --> 15:32.363
- No.
[chuckles]

15:34.325 --> 15:36.226
On the plus side, I didn't
lose either of the twins,

15:36.326 --> 15:38.267
so, you know...

15:38.367 --> 15:40.368
- Great.
[door opens, slams]

15:41.449 --> 15:43.550
- Vivek, we've been
through this.

15:43.650 --> 15:45.512
Don't we trust
each other by now?

15:45.612 --> 15:46.992
- Yes, Denise.

15:47.092 --> 15:49.034
You led the horse to the water,
now drown him!

15:49.134 --> 15:52.036
- What is going on?
- Shh!

15:52.136 --> 15:53.717
- Leave while you still can.

15:53.817 --> 15:56.238
- Oh, Vivek's line
of credit is almost up.

15:56.338 --> 15:58.520
He's leveraged up
the you-know-what.

15:58.620 --> 15:59.560
- Go in for the kill, Mom!

15:59.660 --> 16:00.801
- I don't know
what's happening!

16:00.901 --> 16:01.922
- Okay, here's what
we're gonna to do...

16:02.022 --> 16:04.563
- Okay, enough.
- Oh, Lulu, don't--

16:04.663 --> 16:06.605
- Thank you, we're not
interested in your blood money.

16:06.705 --> 16:08.286
[cell phone beeps]
- No.

16:08.386 --> 16:10.527
- Sarah, that was for a company

16:10.627 --> 16:13.889
that gives micro-loans
to women-owned businesses.

16:13.989 --> 16:15.930
- Well, that's not the point.
What the hell is going on?

16:16.030 --> 16:17.331
- Well, I came
to pick up Kelvin,

16:17.431 --> 16:18.812
and Connor
couldn't close with Jerry.

16:18.912 --> 16:20.693
And then he put me
on the phone with Jerry.

16:20.793 --> 16:23.535
And I got Jerry up to 35%,
which is crazy!

16:23.635 --> 16:24.816
- It's crazy.
- Crazy, can you believe that?

16:24.916 --> 16:26.577
- No!
- Mom!

16:26.677 --> 16:29.259
It's almost 9:00 a.m. in Tokyo.
The Nikkei's about to open!

16:29.359 --> 16:31.580
- Nice, Kelvin.

16:31.680 --> 16:34.542
- Connor, may I speak
with you privately, please?

16:34.642 --> 16:35.743
[line trilling]

16:35.843 --> 16:37.104
Now, Connor!

16:37.204 --> 16:39.745
- Konnichiwa.
Yes, how are you?

16:39.845 --> 16:41.947
- You know, I always thought
Denise was a little soft,

16:42.047 --> 16:43.267
but now...

16:43.367 --> 16:45.749
she's like the sister
I always wanted.

16:45.849 --> 16:47.070
You know what I mean.

16:47.170 --> 16:48.831
- Denise is soft.
What did you do to them?

16:48.931 --> 16:51.032
- Weren't you just saying
you feel bad

16:51.132 --> 16:53.314
because Denise is the only
one who's paying for anything?

16:53.414 --> 16:56.676
Well, Shamiah
just made 90 bucks shorting

16:56.776 --> 16:58.357
a Dutch biotech concern.

16:58.457 --> 17:00.078
- I knew that you were gonna
corrupt Kelvin,

17:00.178 --> 17:02.279
but now you went
and corrupted my whole family.

17:02.379 --> 17:03.880
- Corrupt?
- Yeah.

17:03.980 --> 17:05.761
- Oh.

17:05.861 --> 17:07.042
Okay, I see,
you think what I do

17:07.142 --> 17:08.603
for a living
has nothing to do with you.

17:08.703 --> 17:09.844
- I should hope not.

17:09.944 --> 17:11.045
- Well, let me tell you
something, Sarah.

17:11.145 --> 17:13.486
When I invest
in a company like, say,

17:13.586 --> 17:15.407
a mid-sized tree-care company,

17:15.507 --> 17:17.529
that lowers the cost per unit
of their equipment.

17:17.629 --> 17:19.330
Those savings get filtered
all the way down

17:19.430 --> 17:22.011
from the manufacturer
to the consumer.

17:22.111 --> 17:24.053
And Americans, with a little
more money in the bank,

17:24.153 --> 17:26.974
are far more likely to vote
to fund social services,

17:27.074 --> 17:30.056
services like your old job--

17:30.156 --> 17:33.258
the one where you got to help
all those kids who needed it.

17:33.358 --> 17:35.740
Yeah.

17:35.840 --> 17:37.621
- Are you trying to do
the cerulean blue speech

17:37.721 --> 17:38.942
from "Devil Wears Prada"?

17:39.042 --> 17:40.103
- I thought I could slip
that one by you.

17:40.203 --> 17:41.463
It's a great movie,
though, huh?

17:41.563 --> 17:43.024
- It's a great movie.
I've seen it 5,000 times.

17:43.124 --> 17:44.745
- I mean, there's actors,
and then there's, like--

17:44.845 --> 17:45.786
- Meryl.
- Meryl.

17:45.886 --> 17:47.867
- I mean, come on.
- Sarah.

17:47.967 --> 17:50.709
- [sighs]

17:50.809 --> 17:53.151
[keys clacking]

17:53.251 --> 17:55.792
- Is he doing his homework?

17:55.892 --> 17:58.594
Hey, Kel, you're already
working on your report?

17:58.694 --> 18:00.956
I thought you usually wait till
the last minute on that stuff.

18:01.056 --> 18:02.597
- Uncle Connor taught me

18:02.697 --> 18:05.438
about the importance of
determination and discipline.

18:05.538 --> 18:07.840
- [chuckles]
That's great, buddy!

18:07.940 --> 18:10.041
- He called them
those sweet double Ds.

18:10.141 --> 18:11.362
- Okay.

18:11.462 --> 18:12.843
- I don't think
I said it like that.

18:12.943 --> 18:14.924
- Lulu, I'm sorry
I got so carried away.

18:15.024 --> 18:16.485
It was just such a rush

18:16.585 --> 18:18.566
compared
to teaching second graders.

18:18.666 --> 18:19.967
I mean, it's not every day
you make $85,000

18:20.067 --> 18:22.489
in one phone call.
- You--what?

18:22.589 --> 18:25.451
- I lost it five minutes later,
but it was so much fun.

18:25.551 --> 18:27.972
- You know what?
It's actually okay.

18:28.072 --> 18:29.653
It's kind of nice to being
the level-headed one for once.

18:29.753 --> 18:31.014
- Oh, yes, look at you!

18:31.114 --> 18:32.935
- Look at me!
It probably won't last long.

18:33.035 --> 18:34.496
- Yeah, that makes sense.
- But we tried.

18:34.596 --> 18:35.577
- We did try.
- We did.

18:35.677 --> 18:38.579
[warm music]

18:38.679 --> 18:39.740
♪ ♪

18:39.840 --> 18:41.060
- Hi, everyone.

18:41.160 --> 18:43.542
Welcome to my report
on "Connormetrics."

18:43.642 --> 18:45.943
- Whoo!
- [whistles]

18:46.043 --> 18:47.785
- I learned a lot today,

18:47.885 --> 18:49.946
both from my uncle and my moms.

18:50.046 --> 18:52.507
My uncle taught me
that it's nice to get paid,

18:52.607 --> 18:55.349
but my moms taught me
that it pays to be nice.

18:55.449 --> 18:56.910
♪ ♪

18:57.010 --> 18:59.112
To be clear,
I mean paid both spiritually

18:59.212 --> 19:01.793
and in that sweet, sweet cash.

19:01.893 --> 19:03.034
- Oh.

19:03.134 --> 19:04.835
- I'm so proud of him.

19:04.935 --> 19:06.596
- So, uh, let me try
to understand

19:06.696 --> 19:08.157
what was happening today.

19:08.257 --> 19:10.839
- It's simple, really.
You married an insane person.

19:10.939 --> 19:12.480
[laughs]
- Yeah.

19:12.580 --> 19:14.521
- Look, I was worried that
I wasn't doing enough to help,

19:14.621 --> 19:16.883
so I did way too much,
and then I tried to undo it,

19:16.983 --> 19:18.764
and I did way too little,
but, uh...

19:18.864 --> 19:20.965
[laughs] Look, I just--
I saw that you were upset,

19:21.065 --> 19:23.046
and I probably
should have asked why.

19:23.146 --> 19:24.968
- Yeah, that would
have been a good idea.

19:25.068 --> 19:26.449
- [chuckles]

19:26.549 --> 19:28.050
- I wasn't running
errands today.

19:28.150 --> 19:31.091
I stopped by my old law firm.

19:31.191 --> 19:32.572
- Oh.

19:32.672 --> 19:34.574
- Remember when everyone
was arguing

19:34.674 --> 19:37.215
about who Kelvin should pick,
whose job was the coolest?

19:37.315 --> 19:39.337
Nobody even mentioned me.

19:39.437 --> 19:41.418
It's like no one thinks
of what I do as a job

19:41.518 --> 19:43.379
or even remembers
I used to be a lawyer.

19:43.479 --> 19:44.700
- [sighs]
I mean, I'm sorry.

19:44.800 --> 19:46.221
I didn't pick up on that.

19:46.321 --> 19:47.822
- It made sense for me
to stay at home

19:47.922 --> 19:50.383
when your career was taking
off and I was burnt out.

19:50.483 --> 19:52.465
Now it's been three years,

19:52.565 --> 19:54.146
and, I mean, it's been great,

19:54.246 --> 19:57.188
but also sometimes not.

19:57.288 --> 19:58.829
- Yeah.
[both laugh]

19:58.929 --> 20:00.630
You want to go back to work
at the firm?

20:00.730 --> 20:03.271
- God, no.
I mean, I thought I did.

20:03.371 --> 20:05.833
At first, I was excited
to put on business casual

20:05.933 --> 20:07.714
and see old friends,

20:07.814 --> 20:09.355
but then I remembered
the 16-hour days,

20:09.455 --> 20:12.157
the office politics,
and creepy Gary,

20:12.257 --> 20:13.838
who always offered me
a bite of his sub.

20:13.938 --> 20:15.599
- Ugh.

20:15.699 --> 20:18.761
- I might be ready to go back
to work, but, uh, not there.

20:18.861 --> 20:20.202
Also, I asked,
and they're not hiring.

20:20.302 --> 20:22.003
- [laughs]

20:22.103 --> 20:24.565
Well, look, whatever you want
to do, I'm here to help, okay?

20:24.665 --> 20:27.767
I mean, really help,
not destroy our entire house.

20:27.867 --> 20:29.408
- Thank you.

20:29.508 --> 20:31.089
You know, we shouldn't hide
things from each other.

20:31.189 --> 20:33.490
- Absolutely. I might have
broken the washing machine.

20:33.590 --> 20:35.411
- Sometimes I say
I'm taking a shower,

20:35.511 --> 20:36.932
but then I just get my hair
a little wet,

20:37.032 --> 20:38.373
and I go to sleep
on the bath mat.

20:38.473 --> 20:39.774
- Ooh.
[laughs]

20:39.874 --> 20:40.935
- Thank you.
Thank you.

20:41.035 --> 20:44.097
Mwah, mwah.
[applause]

20:44.197 --> 20:46.198
- You broke
the washing machine?

20:48.559 --> 20:49.940
- Kelvin's report
was fantastic.

20:50.040 --> 20:51.501
- Yeah, as a writer,
I was impressed.

20:51.601 --> 20:53.382
Although the recap
of "The Wolf of Wall Street"

20:53.482 --> 20:54.743
was more graphic
than I expected.

20:54.843 --> 20:57.185
- Yeah.
- Oh, yeah, that was...

20:57.285 --> 20:59.586
- Oh!
Lupe, you baked?

20:59.686 --> 21:01.307
- Yes, and I made a box

21:01.407 --> 21:03.229
and put a sticker
of the bakery on it.

21:03.329 --> 21:05.270
- It's from me.
I-I bought a pie.

21:05.370 --> 21:07.071
- Oh, Sarah, that's so sweet.

21:07.171 --> 21:09.032
- Yep, I used the $47
that I made

21:09.132 --> 21:11.554
helping a rich 26-year-old
take her bulldog

21:11.654 --> 21:13.875
to a podcasting internship.

21:13.975 --> 21:15.716
- All right.
- Yeah.

21:15.816 --> 21:17.758
- Hey, are you gonna
conference me in

21:17.858 --> 21:19.038
if Jerry ever calls again?

21:19.138 --> 21:20.519
Because I feel like I can wring

21:20.619 --> 21:22.440
another 2% of blood
out of that stone.

21:22.540 --> 21:24.542
- Denise, you're starting
to freak me out.
